[src:xtdb/main-readme-adoc] XTDB is an open-source immutable SQL database with comprehensive time-travel.
[src:xtdb/main-readme-adoc] XTDB has been built to simplify application development and address complex data compliance requirements.
[src:xtdb/main-readme-adoc] XTDB embraces a log as the central point of coordination when running as a distributed system.
[src:xtdb/main-readme-adoc] XTDB is licensed under the Mozilla Public License, version 2 or (at your option) any later version.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] A **temporal database** stores data relating to time instances.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] It offers temporal data types and stores information relating to past, present and future time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Temporal databases can be uni-temporal, bi-temporal or tri-temporal.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] More specifically the temporal aspects usually include valid time, transaction time and/or decision time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] A uni-temporal database has one axis of time, either the validity range or the system time range.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] This approach introduces additional complexities.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Temporal databases are in contrast to current databases (not to be confused with currently available databases), which store only facts which are believed to be true at the current time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] With the development of SQL and its attendant use in real-life applications, database users realized that when they added date columns to key fields, some issues arose.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] For example, if a table has a primary key and some attributes, adding a date to the primary key to track historical changes can lead to creation of more rows than intended.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Deletes must also be handled differently when rows are tracked in this way.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] In 1992, this issue was recognized but standard database theory was not yet up to resolving this issue, and neither was the then-newly formalized SQL-92 standard.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Richard Snodgrass proposed in 1992 that temporal extensions to SQL be developed by the temporal database community.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] In response to this proposal, a committee was formed to design extensions to the 1992 edition of the SQL standard (ANSI X3.135.-1992 and ISO/IEC 9075:1992); those extensions, known as TSQL2, were developed during 1993 by this committee.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] In late 1993, Snodgrass presented this work to the group responsible for the American National Standard for Database Language SQL, ANSI Technical Committee X3H2 (now known as NCITS H2).
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The preliminary language specification appeared in the March 1994 ACM SIGMOD Record.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] An attempt was made to incorporate parts of TSQL2 into the new SQL standard SQL:1999, called SQL3.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Parts of TSQL2 were included in a new substandard of SQL3, ISO/IEC 9075-7, called SQL/Temporal.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The TSQL2 approach was heavily criticized by Chris Date and Hugh Darwen.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The ISO project responsible for temporal support was canceled near the end of 2001.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Another difference is replacement of the controversial (prefix) statement modifiers from TSQL2 with a set of temporal predicates.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Other features of SQL:2011 standard related to temporal databases are automatic time period splitting, temporal primary keys, temporal referential integrity, temporal predicates with Allen's interval algebra and time-sliced and sequenced queries.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] John Doe was born on 1975-04-03 in the Kids Hospital of Medicine County, as son of Jack Doe and Jane Doe who lived in Smallville.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Jack Doe proudly registered the birth of his first-born on April 4, 1975 at the Smallville City Hall.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] John grew up as a joyful boy, turned out to be a brilliant student and graduated with honors in 1993.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] After graduation, he went to live on his own in Bigtown.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Although he moved out on 1994-08-26, he forgot to register the change of address officially.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] It was only at the turn of the seasons that his mother reminded him that he had to register, which he did a few days later on 1994-12-27.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Although John had a promising future, his story ends tragically.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] John Doe was accidentally hit by a truck on 2001-04-01.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The coroner reported his date of death on the very same day.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] To store the life of John Doe in a current (non-temporal) database we use a table `person (name, address)`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] John's father officially reported his birth on 1975-04-04.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] On this date a Smallville official inserted the following entry in the database: `Person(John Doe, Smallville)`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Note that the date itself is not stored in the database.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] After graduation, John moves out, but forgets to register his new address.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] John's entry in the database is not changed until 1994-12-27, when he finally reports it.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] A Bigtown official updates his address in the database.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The `person` table now contains `Person(John Doe, Bigtown)`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Note that the information of John living in Smallville has been overwritten, so it is no longer possible to retrieve that information from the database.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] An official accessing the database on 1994-12-28, would be told that John lives in Bigtown.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] More technically: if a database administrator ran the query `SELECT ADDRESS FROM PERSON WHERE NAME='John Doe'` on 1994-12-26, the result would be `Smallville`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Running the same query 2 days later would result in `Bigtown`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Until his death, the database would state that he lived in Bigtown.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] On 2001-04-01, the coroner deletes the John Doe entry from the database.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] After this, running the above query would return no result at all.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Valid time is the time for which a fact is true in the real world.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] A valid time period may be in the past, span the current time, or occur in the future.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] For the example above, to record valid time, the `person` table has two fields added, `valid_from` and `valid_to`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] These specify the period when a person's address is valid in the real world.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] On 1975-04-04, John's father registered his son's birth.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] An official then inserts a new entry into the database stating that John lives in Smallville from April 3.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Note that although the data was inserted on the fourth, the database states that the information is valid since the third.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The official does not yet know if or when John will move to another place, so the `valid_to` field is set to infinity (∞).
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] On 1994-12-27, John reports his new address in Bigtown where he has been living since 1994-08-26.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The original entry `Person (John Doe, Smallville, 1975-04-03, ∞)` is not deleted, but has the `valid_to` attribute updated to reflect that it is now known that John stopped living in Smallville on 1994-08-26.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] When John dies his current entry in the database is updated stating that John does not live in Bigtown any longer.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Transaction time records the time period during which a database entry is accepted as correct.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] This enables queries that show the state of the database at a given time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Transaction time periods can only occur in the past or up to the current time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] In a transaction time table, records are never deleted.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Only new records can be inserted, and existing ones updated by setting their transaction end time to show that they are no longer current.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] To enable transaction time in the example above, two more fields are added to the Person table: `transaction_from` and `transaction_to`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Here, `transaction_from` is the time a transaction was made, and `transaction_to` is the time that the transaction was superseded (which may be infinity if it has not yet been superseded).
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] This makes the table into a bitemporal table.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] What happens if the person's address as stored in the database is incorrect?
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Suppose an official accidentally entered the wrong address or date?
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Or, suppose the person lied about their address for some reason.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Upon discovery of the error, the officials update the database to correct the information recorded.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] But to avoid paying Beachy's exorbitant residence tax, he never reported it to the authorities.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Later during a tax investigation, it is discovered on 2-Feb-2001 that he was in fact in Beachy during those dates.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] To record this fact, the existing entry about John living in Bigtown must be split into two separate records, and a new record inserted recording his residence in Beachy.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] However, this leaves no record that the database ever claimed that he lived in Bigtown during 1995-06-01 to 2000-09-03.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] This might be important to know for auditing reasons, or to use as evidence in the official's tax investigation.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Transaction time allows capturing this changing knowledge in the database, since entries are never directly modified or deleted.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Instead, each entry records when it was entered and when it was superseded (or logically deleted).
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The database records not only what happened in the real world, but also what was officially recorded at different times.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Decision time is an alternative to the transaction time period for recording the time at which a database entry may be accepted as correct.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] This enables queries that show the officially recognized facts at a given time, even if there was a delay in committing those facts to the database.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Support for decision time preserves the entire history and prevents the loss of information during updates.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Decision time periods can only occur in the past or up to the transaction time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] As in a transaction time table, records are never deleted.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Only new records can be inserted, and existing ones updated by setting their decision end time to show that they are no longer current.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] To enable decision time, two more fields are added to a database table: `decision_from` and `decision_to`.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Here, `decision_from` is the time a decision was made, and `decision_to` is the time that the decision was superseded (which may be infinity if it has not yet been superseded).
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] When combined with transaction time, this makes the table into a tritemporal table.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] In this example, a constant 7-day delay is assumed between the decision time and the transaction time when the data is committed to the database.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] A bitemporal model contains both valid and transaction time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] This provides both *historical* and *rollback* information.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Historical information (e.g.: "Where did John live in 1992?") is provided by the valid time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Rollback (e.g.: "In 1992, where did the database believe John lived?") is provided by the transaction time.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The answers to these example questions may not be the same – the database may have been altered since 1992, causing the queries to produce different results.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The valid time and transaction time do not have to be the same for a single fact.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] For example, consider a temporal database storing data about the 18th century.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The valid time of these facts is somewhere between 1701 and 1800.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The transaction time would show when the facts were inserted into the database (for example 1998-01-21).
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] A challenging issue is the support of temporal queries in a transaction time database under evolving schema.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] In order to achieve perfect archival quality it is of key importance to store the data under the schema version under which they first appeared.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] However, even the most simple temporal query rewriting the history of an attribute value would be required to be manually rewritten under each of the schema versions, potentially hundreds as in the case of MediaWiki.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] This process would be particularly taxing for users.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] A proposed solution is to provide automatic query rewriting, although this is not part of SQL or similar standards.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] The following implementations provide temporal features in a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Temporal databases were one of the earliest forms of data version control, and influenced the development of modern data versioning systems.
[src:xtdb/temporal-database] Slowly changing dimensions can be used to model temporal relations.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] XTDB is a ‘bitemporal’ and ‘dynamic’ relational database for handling regulated data.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] XTDB is a transactional system designed for powering applications while also being amenable to analytical querying thanks to its internal columnar architecture built on Apache Arrow.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] XTDB is open source and runs on the JVM.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] XTDB tracks both the **system time** when data is inserted (or `UPDATE`-d) into the database, and also the **valid time** periods that define exactly when a given row/record/document is considered **valid**/**effective** in your application.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] This combination of **system** and **valid** time dimensions is called “bitemporality” and in XTDB all data is bitemporal without having to think about storing or updating additional columns.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] All data is time-versioned automatically.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] This system-maintained time-versioning allows application queries to easily access the correct state of the entire application history “as-at” any given moment, *and* to trivially audit all changes to the database.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] In other words, this unlocks the complete history of data for rich analysis and allows applications to cope with out of order arrival of information, including **corrections** to past data while maintaining a general sense of **immutability**.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] XTDB’s approach to temporality is inspired by SQL:2011, but makes it ubiquitous, practical and transparent during day-to-day development.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] All tables include 4 temporal columns by default which are maintained automatically.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] However queries are assumed to query ‘now’ unless otherwise specified.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] Non-valid historical data is filtered out during low-level processing at the heart of the internal design.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] Unlike most transactional database systems, XTDB implements a columnar data architecture that “separates storage and compute” - this modern, Big-Data-inspired architecture is built around Apache Arrow and commodity object storage (e.g.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] Most importantly, this design reduces operational costs when retaining large volumes of historical data.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] Transaction processing is strictly serial and strongly consistent (ACID), based on deterministic ordering of non-interactive transactions.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] Within a cluster, transactions for each database are processed by a single leader node for that database, which produces an indexed output that the other nodes follow — so writes for a given database happen once, on a single thread, and reads scale out across the cluster.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] This design implies a hard upper limit on transaction throughput, but the key advantage is the concrete information guarantees about *exactly when, how & why* data across the database has changed.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] The columnar engine within XTDB is able to handle “documents” as wide rows in sparse tables, where any given value in a column may contain arbitrarily nested data without any need for upfront schema design.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] The full range of built-in types is supported within these nested structures (i.e. unlike JSONB).
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] This enables developers to easily use XTDB either as a store of loosely structured documents, or as a more traditional normalized database, or both at the same time.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] Unlike typical SQL tables with row-oriented storage, XTDB’s columnar tables are always ‘sparse’ (storing NULLs is cheap) and ‘wide’ (storing lots of columns is efficient).
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] XTDB offers two interoperable query languages - one for reach (SQL) and one for developer productivity (XTQL).
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] SQL in XTDB is a first-class citizen, built to reflect the SQL:2011 standard (which first introduced bitemporal capabilities to the SQL standard) and conforms to a broad suite of SQLite Logic Tests.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] XTQL is a novel relational database language that extends the power of SQL and its standard library to a more composable format that can be written or generated by client libraries using a JSON API.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] The two languages are able to interoperate with 100% parity, meaning application developers can use the APIs as they see fit without sacrificing analytical requirements or compromising on functionality.
[src:xtdb/what-is-xtdb] Through each of these interconnected principles and features XTDB solves the motivating problems in a single, coherent system.
